\begin_layout Subsection
Arbitrage
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Arbitrage is an investment strategy in the market, that allows profit gain,
 and does not cost anyrhing.
 It is 
\series bold
the strongest force
\series default
 in the determination of prices of various financial instruments.
 It forces similar cash flows to be priced in a similar way.
 For example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
DF_{0}<DF_{1}<\ldots<DF_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Otherwise, there would have been an arbitrage opportunity (borrow the money
 to repay a debt).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whenever there is an arbitrage opportunity, everyone 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

jumps
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on it, and the natural forces of supply and demand lead to a neq equilibrium.
 For example, given prices of several strips/T-bills, we can construct a
 single 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

syntetic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 bond which is equivalent to all them together, and compare its price to
 the original bond price.
 The arbitraege opportunity can be exploited by 
\series bold
shorting
\series default
 (borrow, use the money in the market.
 An 
\series bold
arbitrage table
\series default
 describes the required strategy and the relevant cash flows.
\end_layout

